📄 OpenShift/Kubernetes Log Explorer — System Design Document


---

1. 🎯 Overview

This system is a local developer tool for exploring Kubernetes/OpenShift logs in a stable, non-streaming, snapshot-based manner.

The goal is to provide a Kibana-like debugging experience without real-time streaming complexity, ensuring:

Predictable UI behavior

No lost context

No log duplication

No scroll instability

Full control over updates



---

2. 🧱 Technology Stack

Frontend

React (Vite)

TypeScript

TailwindCSS

shadcn/ui

Zustand (state management)

react-window (virtualized rendering)


Backend

Node.js (LTS)

Koa (REST API framework)

child_process.spawn (for oc CLI only)

No WebSockets

No database

No external logging systems



---

3. 🧭 System Architecture

Frontend (React)
    ↓ REST API
Backend (Koa)
    ↓
OpenShift CLI (oc)

The backend acts as a stateless wrapper over oc commands.


---

4. 🔄 Core Data Flow

The system enforces a strict hierarchical selection flow:

Projects → Deployments → Pods → Logs

Each step depends on the previous one.


---

5. 🧩 Backend Design (Koa)

5.1 Projects API

Endpoint

GET /api/projects

Implementation

oc get projects -o json


---

5.2 Deployments API

Endpoint

GET /api/deployments?project=<name>

Implementation

oc get deployments -n <project> -o json


---

5.3 Pods API

Endpoint

GET /api/pods?project=<name>

Implementation

oc get pods -n <project> -o json

Notes

Pods must be filtered by deployment labels in backend logic.



---

5.4 Logs (Initial Snapshot)

Endpoint

GET /api/logs?project=<p>&pod=<pod>&tail=<N>

Implementation

oc logs <pod> -n <project> --tail=<N>


---

5.5 Logs Refresh

Endpoint

GET /api/logs/refresh?project=<p>&pod=<pod>&since=<timestamp>

Implementation

oc logs <pod> -n <project> --since-time=<timestamp>


---

6. 🧠 Logging Model (Critical)

6.1 Log Object Structure

Each log line is normalized into:

type Log = {
  id: number
  timestamp: string
  level: "INFO" | "WARN" | "ERROR" | "DEBUG" | "TRACE"
  message: string
  raw: string
}


---

6.2 State Model (Frontend)

logs: Log[]
pendingLogs: Log[]
lastSeenTimestamp: string
newLogsCount: number

selectedProject: string
selectedDeployment: string
selectedPod: string
tailSize: number

autoRefresh: boolean


---

7. 📥 Data Loading Strategy

7.1 Initial Load

1. Fetch logs using --tail=N


2. Sort by timestamp ascending


3. Assign sequential IDs


4. Store lastSeenTimestamp


5. Render logs




---

7.2 Refresh Flow (CRITICAL)

Step 1: Fetch new logs

oc logs --since-time=<lastSeenTimestamp>

Step 2: Deduplicate

A log is duplicate if:

timestamp + message match existing log



---

Step 3: Buffer (DO NOT render immediately)

pendingLogs.push(newLogs)
newLogsCount += newLogs.length


---

Step 4: UI decision

Logs are only merged into UI when user explicitly clicks:

> “Show new logs”




---

Step 5: Merge process

logs = [...logs, ...pendingLogs]
logs = reindexSequentially(logs)
lastSeenTimestamp = logs[last].timestamp
pendingLogs = []
newLogsCount = 0


---

8. 🔄 Auto Refresh System

Interval-based polling (2s–10s)

Uses same refresh endpoint

MUST NOT:

modify visible logs directly

trigger scroll changes

re-render full dataset



Only updates:

pendingLogs

newLogsCount



