9. 🖥 Frontend Architecture

9.1 Layout Structure

TOP BAR
LEFT DRAWER | MAIN LOG VIEW | RIGHT DRAWER


---

9.2 LEFT DRAWER (Navigation)

Contains searchable dropdowns:

Project selector

Deployment selector

Pod selector

Tail size selector


Rules:

Must support typeahead search

Must be hierarchical (project → deployment → pod)

Must enforce single pod selection



---

9.3 TOP BAR (Controls)

Search input

Regex toggle

Refresh button

Auto-refresh toggle

Interval selector

Log level filters



---

9.4 RIGHT DRAWER (Inspector)

Opens on log click:

JSON tree viewer (if applicable)

Raw log view

Metadata:

timestamp

pod

project


Copy actions



---

9.5 MAIN LOG VIEW

Virtualized rendering (react-window)

No auto-scroll

Stable DOM updates only

Each log rendered as:


#index timestamp LEVEL message


---

10. 🔍 Search System

Instant filtering

Regex mode supported

Highlight matches

Does NOT mutate underlying log data



---

11. 🔢 Log Numbering

Sequential index per session

Persistent across refresh

Resets only when switching pod



---

12. 🎨 UI/UX Requirements

Typography

UI: Inter

Logs: JetBrains Mono

Minimum size: 14px


Design Principles

High readability

Low density

No layout shifting

Kibana-like inspection panel

VSCode-like responsiveness



---

13. ⚠️ Edge Cases

High log volume

Display warning:

“Some logs may be skipped due to high volume”


Duplicate logs

Must be removed during merge

Missing timestamps

Fallback to order of arrival


---

14. 🚫 Forbidden Behaviors

No live streaming (-f)

No WebSockets

No multi-pod logs

No backend state persistence

No auto-scroll

No time-window UI

No log grouping/clustering engines

No full re-render on refresh



---

15. 🎯 Success Criteria

The system is correct only if:

Logs remain stable during refresh

No UI jumps occur

No duplicate logs appear

Search works with regex

Single pod context is enforced

Inspector behaves like Kibana panel

Refresh is explicit and controlled



---

🧠 Core Principle

> Logs are not streamed. They are queried, buffered, and revealed only when explicitly requested by the user.




